## What happened

.NET 11 removed the DSA implementation on macOS. Apple's Security framework has never supported DSA natively, and Microsoft finally dropped the OpenSSL-based fallback that earlier runtimes used. Calling `DSA.Create()` now throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS.

DSA has been deprecated by NIST since 2023 (FIPS 186-5 removed it for signature generation), so Microsoft classified it as legacy and removed cross-platform support where no native OS backing exists.

## How to fix it

**Option 1 – Migrate away from DSA (preferred)**  
If you control the signing side, re-sign with ECDSA or Ed25519 and update verification accordingly.

**Option 2 – Use BouncyCastle for verification (if you must keep DSA)**  
```csharp
// dotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Security;

public static bool VerifyDsaSignature(byte[] message, byte[] signature, DsaPublicKeyParameters pubKey)
{
    var signer = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA256withDSA");
    signer.Init(forSigning: false, pubKey);
    signer.BlockUpdate(message, 0, message.Length);
    return signer.VerifySignature(signature);
}
```

**Option 3 – Conditional runtime with OpenSSL on macOS**  
Ship OpenSSL via Homebrew/bundled dylib and P/Invoke into it, but this adds deployment complexity.

## Summary

| Approach | Effort | Long-term viability |
|----------|--------|---------------------|
| Migrate to ECDSA/EdDSA | Medium | ✅ Best |
| BouncyCastle managed DSA | Low | ⚠️ OK for verification-only |
| Bundle OpenSSL on macOS | High | ❌ Fragile |

If the signatures are from a third-party you can't change, BouncyCastle is the quickest unblock.
